ukaddasi |authorlink=Al-Muqaddasi |year=1886 |url=https://archive.org/details/cu31924028534265 |title= Description of Syria, including Palestine |location =London | publisher =  [[Palestine Pilgrims' Text Society]] }}   \n*{{cite book|last=Palmer|first=E.H.|authorlink=Edward Henry Palmer|year=1881|url=http://www.archive.org/details/surveyofwesternp00conduoft|title=The Survey of Western Palestine: Arabic and English Name Lists Collected During the Survey by Lieutenants Conder and Kitchener, R. E. Transliterated and Explained by E.H. Palmer|publisher=[[Palestine Exploration Fund|Committee of the Palestine Exploration Fund]]}} \n*{{cite book|last=Petersen |first=Andrew |title=A Gazetteer of Buildings in Muslim Palestine (British Academy Monographs in Archaeology)|url= https://www.academia.edu/21539664/Gazetteer_4_D-J |volume =1  |year=2001|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|isbn=978-0-19-727011-0}}\n*Petersen, A. (2008): ''[https://www.academia.edu/2635988/Bridges_in_Medieval_Palestine Bridges in Medieval Palestine]'', in U. Vermeulen & K. Dhulster (eds.), [http://www.peeters-leuven.be/boekoverz.asp?nr=8299 History of Egypt & Syria in the Fatimid, Ayyubid & Mamluk Eras V], V. Peeters, Leuven\n*{{cite book|last1=Robinson|first1=E.|authorlink1=Edward Robinson (scholar)|last2=Smith|first2=E.|authorlink2=Eli Smith|year=1841|url=http://archive.org/details/biblicalresearc00smitgoog |title=Biblical Researches in Palestine, Mount Sinai and Arabia Petraea: A Journal of Travels in the year 1838|  location=Boston|publisher=[[Crocker & Brewster]]|volume=2}}  [https://archive.org/stream/biblicalresearc00smitgoog#page/n282/mode/1up  260] app. 168\n*{{cite book|last1=Robinson|first1=E.|authorlink1=Edward Robinson (scholar)|last2=Smith|first2=E.|authorlink2=Eli Smith|year=1856|url=http://archive.org/details/laterbiblicalre01smitgoog   |title=Later Biblical Researches in Palestine and adjacent regions: A Journal of Travels in the year 1852|  location=London|publisher=[[John Murray (publisher)|John Murray]]}}  (pp. [http://archive.org/stream/laterbiblicalre01smitgoog#page/n389/mode/1up 340]-1)\n*{{cite book|title=Corpus Inscriptionum Arabicarum Palaestinae, A |volume= 1|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=j1rSzWgHMjoC|first=M.|last=Sharon|authorlink=Moshe Sharon|year=1997|publisher=BRILL|isbn=90-04-10833-5}}\n*{{cite book|title=Corpus Inscriptionum Arabicarum Palaestinae, G |url= http://books.google.com/books?id=P2LtyFVNJmcC |first=M.|last=Sharon|authorlink1=Moshe Sharon|year=2009|volume =4| publisher=BRILL|isbn=90-04-17085-5}} \n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.palestineremembered.com/GeoPoints/Jisr_al_Majami__1802/index.html  Welcome To Jisr al-Majami']\n*[http://www.davidrumsey.com/luna/servlet/workspace/handleMediaPlayer?qvq=q%3aAuthor%3dJacotin%3blc%3aRUMSEY~8~1&trs=50&mi=48&lunaMediaId=RUMSEY~8~1~25537~1020116  Jacotin, Plate 46]\n*Survey of Western Palestine, Map 9: [http://www.iaa-archives.org.il/zoom/zoom.aspx?folder_id=93&type_id=6&id=8371   IAA], [http://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Survey_of_Western_Palestine_1880.09.jpg Wikimedia commons]\n*[http://archnet.org/sites/4310/media_contents/35398  Jisr al-Majami], picture, archnet\n*[https://www.google.com/maps/@32.624464,35.5643319,3a,75y,86.36h,76.98t/data=!3m6!1e1!3m4!1sHKw37EqYawcyGkmHY3_5cQ!2e0!7i13312!8i6656?hl=en  Jisr al Majami, google-maps]\n\n[[Category:Bridges over the Jordan River]]\n[[Category:Bridges in Israel]]\n[[Category:Roman bridges]]\n[[Category:Roman sites in Israel]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox bridge|\n|image         = 0069\u05d2\u05e9\u05e8 \u05d4\u05db\u05d1\u05d9\u05e9 \u05de\u05e2\u05dc \u05d4\u05d9\u05e8\u05d3\u05df \u05e9\u05e4\u05d5\u05e6\u05e5 \u05d1 48 \u05d1\u05dc\u05d9\u05dc \u05d4\u05d2\u05e9\u05e8\u05d9\u05dd \u05d1\u05d2\u05e9\u05e8 \u05d4\u05d9\u05e9\u05e0\u05d4.jpg\n|bridge_name   = Jisr Majami\n|official_name = Jisr Majami\n|locale        = [[Gesher, Israel]] and Baqoura, Jordan\n|crosses       = [[Jordan River]]\n|open          = Roman era\n|below=\n|design        = [[Arch bridge|Arch]]\n|length        = c. 70 m<ref name=Petersen186>Petersen, 2001, p. [https://www.academia.edu/21539664/Gazetteer_4_D-J 186]</ref>\n|width         = c. 18 m\n|height        = 10 m<ref name=Petersen186/>\n}}\n'''Jisr Majami''' or '''Jisr al Mujamieh''', ({{lang-ar|\u062c\u0633\u0631 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u062c\u0627\u0645\u0639|lit=Meeting Bridge or \"The bridge of the place of assembling\"|translit=Jisr al Majami}}<ref>Palmer, 1881, p. [http://archive.org/stream/surveyofwesternp00conduoft#page/161/mode/1up 161]</ref> and {{lang-he-n|\u05d2\u05b6\u05bc\u05e9\u05b6\u05c1\u05e8|lit=Bridge|translit=Gesher}}) is a [[list of Roman bridges|Roman bridge]] over the [[Jordan River]] on the border between [[Israel]] and [[Jordan]]. The name is derived from the bridge's location 200 meters south of the [[confluence]] of the Yarmouk and Jordan rivers.<ref>[https://archive.org/details/byewaysinpalesti00finniala/page/104/mode/2up Byeways in Palestine], 1868, p.104-105: \"The name is derived from the meeting of two branches of the Jordan in that place after having separated above.\"</ref><ref name=Petersen296>Petersen, 2008, p. [https://www.academia.edu/2635988/Bridges_in_Medieval_Palestine 296]</ref>\n\n==Description==\nThe bridge is 70 meters long, with one main arch through which the water normally flow. In addition it has 6 smaller arches, higher up in a second row, presumably to help the flow during flooding of the river. The main arch is the only one which has a permanent flow of water.<ref name=Petersen186/>\nThe bridge has [[voussoirs]] throughout its [[Vault (architecture)|vault]], differing from well known Mamluk bridges such as the [[Daughters of Jacob Bridge]], [[Yibna Bridge]] and [[Jisr Jindas]], which use small stones in the vault of their arches.<ref name=Petersen296/>\n\n==History==\n===Roman period===\nThe bridge shows at least two major phases of construction; a possibly Roman-origin lower level and the upper pointed arches likely from the medieval period.<ref name=Petersen296/> Some sources state that the bridge was built in Roman times, and others that it was built in the middle ages. A 1925 letter written by the Palestine Department of Antiquities wrote that the bridge was first built in Roman times.<ref name=Petersen186/> This is supported by a Roman [[milestone]] discovered nearby, which given the scarcity of other local structures makes it likely that a Roman river crossing existed at the point.<ref name=Petersen186/>\n\n===Middle ages===\n[[Al-Muqaddasi]] (c. 945/946 - 991),  described \"beyond the lower end of the [[Sea of Galilee|Lake of Tiberias]] is a great bridge, over which lies the road to [[Damascus]]\",<ref>Mukaddasi, 1886, p. [https://archive.org/stream/cu31924028534265#page/n52/mode/1up 27]</ref><ref>Le Strange, 1890, p. [http://www.archive.org/stream/palestineundermo00lestuoft#page/335/mode/1up 335]</ref><ref>See note 2, Mukaddasi, 1886, p. [https://archive.org/stream/cu31924028534265#page/n52/mode/1up 27]</ref> however, Andrew Petersen believes that Al-Muqaddasi may have been referring to [[Jisr es-Sidd]], further north (by  [[Al-Manshiyya, Tiberias|Um al-Junah]], near modern-day [[Degania Bet]]).<ref name=Petersen186/>\n\n[[Shihab al-Umari]], writing in the mid 1300s, wrote of a renovated stop en route from [[Beisan]] to [[Irbid]] called Jisr al Mujami, also knows as Jisr Usama.<ref name=Petersen186/> A manuscript in the [[Biblioth\u00e8que nationale de France]] states that it was built by Mamluk sultan [[Barquq]].<ref>Clermont-Ganneau, 1896, vol.2, p. [https://archive.org/stream/archaeologicalre02cler#page/117/mode/1up 117], who quotes the [[Cartulaire g\u00e9n\u00e9ral de l'ordre des Hospitaliers]], no.84</ref>\n\nThe bridge underwent at least two major repairs during medieval times, by Usama al Halabi during the reign of [[Saladin]] (1174-93), and one by a \"Jamal ad-Din\" in 1266-67.<ref name=Petersen296/> An epitaph of a Muslim, from [[Bitlis]], who drowned at Jisr al Majami in October 1308 has been found under the Ottoman floor in the Khan.<ref>Sharon, 2009,  pp. [http://books.google.com/books?id=P2LtyFVNJmcC&pg=PA214  214]-[http://books.google.com/books?id=P2LtyFVNJmcC&pg=PA216 216]</ref>\n\n===Early modern===\n[[File:Jisr al Majami.png|thumb|1799 map  (detail) by [[Pierre Jacotin]]]]\nA map from [[French campaign in Egypt and Syria|Napoleon's invasion of 1799]] by [[Pierre Jacotin]]  showed the bridge, named as ''Pont de Magama'', and the adjacent Khan, marked ''Caravanserail''.<ref>Karmon, 1960, p. [http://www.jchp.ucla.edu/Bibliography/Karmon,_Y_1960_Jacotin_Map_(IEJ_10).pdf 164]</ref><ref name=Mokary195>Mokary and Gil, 2005, p. 195</ref> \n\n[[James Finn]] wrote in 1868 that the bridge was \"in tolerably good condition, with one large and several smaller arches in two rows, and a dilapidated khan at the western end... The khan has been a strong edifice, but the stones of the massive gateway, especially the great keystone, are split across, as if from the effects of gunpowder.\" Finn noted a story of \"the wandering minstrels, even now among the Bedaween, sing the songs of the forty orphan youths who competed in poetic compositions under the influence of love for an Arab maiden at the bridge of Mejama'a.\"<ref>[https://archive.org/details/byewaysinpalesti00finniala/page/104/mode/2up Byeways in Palestine], 1868, p.104-105</ref> The [[Palestine Exploration Fund|PEF]]'s [[PEF Survey of Palestine|''Survey of Western Palestine'' (SWP)]] noted that the name was related to  the \"Bridge of the Gatherer\", which became the [[As-Sir\u0101t]].<ref>Conder and Kitchener, 1882, p. [http://www.archive.org/stream/surveyofwesternp02conduoft#page/132/mode/1up 132]</ref>\n\n===20th century===\nThe bridge played a strategic role in [[World War I]]; it was captured by the [[19th Lancers]] during the [[Capture of Afulah and Beisan]]. When the Rutenberg concession was given, it was defined as the area around Jisr Majami.\n\nThe bridge was damaged during the 1948 War, primarily caused by the explosion of mines placed on the parallel 1920s road bridge.<ref name=ICR/>\n\n===2014 renovation===\n[[File:RENOVATION IN GESHER.jpg|thumb|2014 renovations]]\nIt was renovated in 2014 by the [[Ministry of Cultural Heritage and Activities (Italy)|Italian Ministry of Cultural Heritage and Activities]] together with the [[Department of Antiquities (Jordan)|Jordanian Department of Antiquities]] and the [[Israel Antiquities Authority]].<ref name=ICR>Alessandro Bianchi, Fabio De Angelis, Pietro Gasparri, Giuseppe Morganti, Simona Pannuzi, Carlo Usai, [http://www.icr.beniculturali.it/documenti/allegati/Abstract_english_34.pdf Restoration of Jisr el-Majami\u2019 Bridge on the Jordan River], Bollettino iCR \u2022 nuova Serie \u2022 n. 34 \u2022 2017</ref>\n\n==Other bridges==\nA railway bridge was built parallel to it in the early 20th century to carry to [[Jezreel Valley railway]], opened in 1905, and a road bridge was built in the early 1920s. \n\n==Khan and village==\n{{see also|Gesher, Israel}}\n[[File:Lands Acquired in the Vicinity of the Jordan Works in Palestine and Transjordania, from the Palestine Electric Company Archives.jpg|thumb|The land surrounding the bridge was acquired by Palestine Electric Company in the 1920s.]]\nAround 1365 the  [[Caravanserai|Khan]] was built at  Jisr al Majami.<ref>Sharon, 1997, p. [https://books.google.com/books?id=EPFDU8POrXIC&pg=PA229 229]</ref>\n\nIn 1875 [[Victor Gu\u00e9rin]] visited, and noted the remains of the deserted Khan. The Khan was two stories high, built around a courtyard. It was built of [[basalt]] stones, with the gates done in the [[ablaq]] style; alternating white and black stones. The Khan had only one entry. Not far from the Khan Gu\u00e9rin noted the ancient bridge, with a central arch being much larger than the side-arches.<ref>Gu\u00e9rin, 1880, pp. [http://archive.org/stream/descriptiongogr01unkngoog#page/n146/mode/1up 133]-134,    [http://archive.org/stream/descriptiongogr01unkngoog#page/n298/mode/1up 285]</ref>[[File:\u05de\u05e2\u05d1\u05e8\u05d9 \u05d4\u05d9\u05e8\u05d3\u05df \u05d0\u05ea\u05e8 \u05d2\u05e9\u05e8 \u05d4\u05d9\u05e9\u05e0\u05d4.jpg|thumb|left|2014 aerial view showing all three bridges and the old khan.]]In 1882  the [[Palestine Exploration Fund|PEF]]'s [[PEF Survey of Palestine|''Survey of Western Palestine'' (SWP)]] described a \"ruined Khan, or 'hostel', a large square building with vaults beneath, still in a good state of preservation.\"<ref>Conder and Kitchener, 1882, SWP II, p.  [http://www.archive.org/stream/surveyofwesternp02conduoft#page/116/mode/1up 116]</ref>\n\nA small settlement in the caravanserai existed until the early 20th century,<ref>Petersen, 2001, p. [https://www.academia.edu/21539664/Gazetteer_4_D-J 186]: \"During the mandate period there was a small village at the site although all trace of this has now disappeared.\"</ref> in the [[1922 census of Palestine]], conducted by the [[Mandate for Palestine|British Mandate authorities]], Jisr al Majami had a population of 121; 112 Muslims, 4 Jews and 5 Christians,<ref name=Census1922a>Barron, 1923,  Table IX, Sub-district of Baisan, p. [https://archive.org/stream/PalestineCensus1922/Palestine%20Census%20%281922%29#page/n33/mode/1up  31]</ref> where all the Christians were of the Orthodox faith.<ref name=Census1922b>Barron, 1923,  Table XV,  p. [https://archive.org/stream/PalestineCensus1922/Palestine%20Census%20%281922%29#page/n50/mode/1up 48]</ref>  \n\nFollowing the building of the [[Naharayim|Rutenberg hydroelectric power plant]], the population had totally changed in the [[1931 census of Palestine|1931 census]]  to a total of 320;  3  Muslim, 316 Jews and 3 Christian, in a total of in 43 houses.<ref name=\"Census1931\">Mills, 1932, p. [https://ia800304.us.archive.org/18/items/CensusOfPalestine1931.PopulationOfVillagesTownsAndAdministrativeAreas/PalestineCensus1931.pdf   79]</ref>\nIn  [[Village Statistics, 1945|1945]]   Jisr al Majami had 250 inhabitants; 230 Jews, 10 Muslims and 10 Christians, and the total land area was 458 dunams.<ref name=1945p6>Department of Statistics, 1945, p. [http://users.cecs.anu.edu.au/~bdm/yabber/census/VSpages/VS1945_p06.jpg 6]</ref><ref>Government of Palestine, Department of Statistics. ''Village Statistics, April, 1945.'' Quoted in  Hadawi, 1970, p. [http://www.palestineremembered.com/download/VillageStatistics/Table%20I/Baysan/Page-043.jpg  43]</ref>  A total of 15 [[Dunam|dunums]] were used for [[citrus]] and [[banana]]s, 274 dunums were used for cereals,<ref>Government of Palestine, Department of Statistics. ''Village Statistics, April, 1945.'' Quoted in  Hadawi, 1970, p. [http://www.palestineremembered.com/download/VillageStatistics/Table%20II/Baysan/Page-084.jpg 84]</ref> while 169 dunams were classified as uncultivable land.<ref>Government of Palestine, Department of Statistics. ''Village Statistics, April, 1945.'' Quoted in  Hadawi, 1970, p. [http://www.palestineremembered.com/download/VillageStatistics/Table%20III/Baysan/Page-134.jpg  134]</ref> \n\nThe area was evacuated during the 1948 war and rebuilt approximately 2 km southwest in what is now [[Gesher, Israel]].\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Guarding Jisr Mujimie Bridge Art.IWMART1698.jpg|1919 sketch, showing much of the old Khan standing\nFile:Jisr Mujimie Bridge Art.IWMART1592.jpg|1919 sketch\nFile:Abbud.Jisr Majamie.JPG|The Ottoman railway bridge, photo by [[Karimeh Abbud]],  late 1920s\nFile:Jisr Majami.jpg|1924, prior to the construction of the parallel road bridge\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Jisr Jindas]]\n*[[List of Roman bridges]]\n*[[Daughters of Jacob Bridge]]\n\n==References==\n{{coord|32|38|41.1|N|35|34|22.7|E|region:SY_type:city|display=title}}\n{{reflist|25em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{ref begin}}\n*{{cite book | editor =Barron,  J.B. | title = Palestine: Report and General Abstracts of the Census of 1922 |url=http://archive.org/details/PalestineCensus1922   |publ