=BRILL|isbn=90-04-17085-5}} \n{{refend}}\n==External links==\n*[http://www.palestineremembered.com/GeoPoints/Jisr_al_Majami__1802/index.html  Welcome To Jisr al-Majami']\n*[http://www.davidrumsey.com/luna/servlet/workspace/handleMediaPlayer?qvq=q%3aAuthor%3dJacotin%3blc%3aRUMSEY~8~1&trs=50&mi=48&lunaMediaId=RUMSEY~8~1~25537~1020116  Jacotin, Plate 46]\n*Survey of Western Palestine, Map 9: [http://www.iaa-archives.org.il/zoom/zoom.aspx?folder_id=93&type_id=6&id=8371   IAA], [http://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Survey_of_Western_Palestine_1880.09.jpg Wikimedia commons]\n*[http://archnet.org/sites/4310/media_contents/35398  Jisr al-Majami], picture, archnet\n*[https://www.google.com/maps/@32.624464,35.5643319,3a,75y,86.36h,76.98t/data=!3m6!1e1!3m4!1sHKw37EqYawcyGkmHY3_5cQ!2e0!7i13312!8i6656?hl=en  Jisr al Majami, google-maps]\n[[Category:Bridges over the Jordan River]]\n[[Category:Bridges in Israel]]\n[[Category:Roman bridges]]\n[[Category:Roman sites in Israel]]\n", "name_user": "CAPTAIN RAJU", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up,typo(s) fixed: middle ages \u2192 Middle Ages, 1266-67 \u2192 1266\u201367", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jisr_Majami"}
{"title_page": "Sandy Skoglund", "text_new": "{{Infobox artist\n| name          = Sandy Skoglund\n| image= Artist Sandy Skoglund, 2013 (cropped).jpg\n| caption=Skoglund in 2013\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1946|9|11|mf=y}}\n| birth_place   = [[Weymouth, Massachusetts]], U.S.\n| nationality   = American\n| field         = [[Photography]], [[Sculpture]], [[installation art|Installation]]\n| training      = [[Smith College]], [[Massachusetts]] / [[University of Iowa]], [[Iowa]]\n| movement      = [[Surrealism]]\n| works         = ''Radioactive Cats'' (1980)<br/>''Sock Situation'' (1986)<br/>''The Cocktail Party'' (1992)<br/>''Shimmering Madness'' (1998)<br/>''Raining Pop Corn'' (2001)\n| website = http://www.sandyskoglund.com/\n}}\n'''Sandy Skoglund''' (born September 11, 1946) is an American photographer and installation artist.<ref>{{cite news\n|title=Art in Review\n|author=Charles Hagen\n|date=September 23, 1994\n|newspaper=[[dagbladet]]\n|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/09/23/arts/art-in-review-329347.html?pagewanted=1?pagewanted=1\n|accessdate=2010-07-22\n}}</ref>\n\nSkoglund creates [[surrealist]] images by building elaborate sets or [[Tableaux Vivant|tableaux]], furnishing them with carefully selected colored furniture and other objects, a process of which takes her months to complete. Finally, she photographs the set, mostly including live models.  The works are characterized by an overwhelming amount of one object and either bright, contrasting colors or a monochromatic color scheme.<ref>[http://www.artnet.com/artist/659254/sandy-skoglund.html]</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nSkoglund was born in [[Weymouth, Massachusetts]] on September 11, 1946. She spent her childhood all over the country including the states Maine, Connecticut, and California. She studied both [[art history]] and [[studio art]] at [[Smith College]] in [[Northampton, Massachusetts|Northampton]], Massachusetts, graduating in 1968. In 1967, she studied art history through her college's study abroad program at the [[University of Paris|Sorbonne]] and [[\u00c9cole du Louvre]] in [[Paris]], [[France]]. After graduating in 1969, she went to graduate school at the [[University of Iowa]], where she studied [[cinematography|filmmaking]], [[multimedia]] [[art]], and [[printmaking]]. In 1971, she earned her Master of Arts and in 1972 a Master of Fine Arts in [[painting]].<ref>{{cite web\n |title        = Sandy Skogland Biography\n |publisher    = Art Galleries Switzerland\n |url          = http://guybae.artgalleries.ch/index.html?page_id=18&change_lid=1\n |accessdate   = 2007-08-26\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20070929004123/http://guybae.artgalleries.ch/index.html?page_id=18&change_lid=1#\n |archive-date = 2007-09-29\n |url-status     = dead\n}}</ref>\n\nIn 1972, Skoglund began working as a conceptual artist in [[New York City]]. She taught herself photography to document her artistic endeavors, and experimenting with themes of repetition.  She also become interested in advertising and high technology--trying to marry the commercial look with a noncommercial purpose, combining the technical focus found in the commercial world and bringing that into the fine art studio.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Tarlow|first=Lois|date=|title=Sandy Skoglund|url=|journal=Art New England|volume=19|pages=25|via=Art & Architecture Source}}</ref> Skoglund created repetitive, process-oriented art  through the techniques of mark-making and photocopying. For example, her 1973 ''Crumpled and Copied'' artwork centered on her repeatedly crumpled and photocopied a piece of paper.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.oxfordartonline.com/groveart/view/10.1093/gao/9781884446054.001.0001/oao-9781884446054-e-7000097698|title=Skoglund, Sandy|website=Grove Art Online|year=2002|language=en|doi=10.1093/gao/9781884446054.article.t097698|access-date=2020-03-31|last1=Grant|first1=Catherine M.}}</ref> In 1978, she had produced a series of repetitious food item still life images. These photographs of food were presented in geometric and brightly colored environments so that the food becomes an integral part to the overall patterning, as in Cubed Carrots and Kernels of Corn,<ref name=\":0\" />with its checkerboard of carrots on a white-spotted red plate placed on a cloth in the same pattern.  Skoglund's works are quirky and idiosyncratic, and as former photography critic for [[The New York Times]] [[Andy Grundberg]] describes, they \"evoke adult fears in a playful, childlike context\".\n\nOne of her most-known works, entitled ''Radioactive Cats'', features green-painted clay cats running amok in a gray kitchen. An older man sits in a chair with his back facing the camera while his elderly wife looks into a refrigerator that is the same color as the walls. \"The artist sculpted the life-size cats herself using chicken wire and plaster, and painted them bright green. She acquired used furniture and constructed a painted gray set, then asked two elderly neighbors living in her apartment building in New York City to pose as models.\"<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Dalton|first=Robert|date=|title=Interpreting and Responding to Contemporary Photography through Creative Writing.|url=|journal=Canadian Review of Art Education: Research & Issues|volume=42|pages=12\u201326|via=Art & Architecture Source}}</ref> The end product is a very evocative photograph.  In an on-line  Getty Center for Education in the Arts forum,Terry Barrett and Sydney Walker (2013) identify two viable interpretations of Radioactive Cats. The first is about social indifference to the elderly and the second is nuclear war and its aftermath, suggested by the artist\u2019s title.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nHer 1990 work, \"Fox Games'' has a similar feel to ''Radioactive Cats\";it unleashes the imagination of the viewer is allowed to roam freely. A third and final often recognized piece by her features numerous fish hovering above people in bed late at night and is called [[Revenge of the Goldfish (photograph)|Revenge of the Goldfish]].  The piece was used as cover art for the [[Inspiral Carpets]] album of the same name.<ref>[http://www.artcyclopedia.com/artists/skoglund_sandy.html]</ref>\n\nSkoglund was an art professor at the [[University of Hartford]] between 1973 and 1976. She is currently teaching photography and art installation/multimedia at [[Rutgers University]] in [[New Jersey]].\n\nIn 2000, the Galerie Guy B\u00e4rtschi in Geneva, Switzerland held an exhibition of 30 works by Sandy Skoglund, which served as a modest retrospective. The photographs ranged from the plates on tablecloths of the late 1970s to the more spectacular works of the 1980s and 1990s. The critic who reviewed the exhibition, Richard Leydier, commented that Skoglund criticism is littered with interpretations of all kinds, whether feminist, sociological, psychoanalytical or whatever. But, Skoglund claims not to be aware of these reading, saying, \"What is the meaning of my work? For me, it's really in doing it.\"<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Leydier|first=Richard|date=|title=Sandy Skoglund: Galerie Guy B\u00e4rtschi.|url=|journal=Art-Press|volume=no. 257|pages=65\u201366|via=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, Skoglund completed a series titled \"True Fiction Two\". This project is similar to the \"True Fiction\" series that she began in 1986. This series was not completed due to the discontinuation of materials that Skoglund was using. Kodak canceled the production of the dye that Skoglund was using for her prints. Each image in \"True Fiction Two\" has been meticulously crafted to assimilate the visual and photographic possibilities now available in digital processes.\n\nHer works are held in numerous museum collections including the [[Museum of Contemporary Photography]],<ref>[http://www.mocp.org/collections/permanent/skoglund_sandy.php mocp.org]</ref> [[San Francisco Museum of Modern Art]]<ref>[http://www.sfmoma.org/artists/4301/artwork sfmoma.org] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100728025508/http://www.sfmoma.org/artists/4301/artwork |date=2010-07-28 }}</ref>, [[Montclair Art Museum]] and [[Dayton Art Institute]].<ref>http://www.daytonartinstitute.org/art/collection-highlights/american/shimmering-madness</ref>\n\nSkoglund holds a faculty position at the Department of Arts, Culture and Media of [[University of Rutgers\u2013Newark]] in [[Newark, New Jersey]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [http://www.sandyskoglund.com/ Sandy Skoglund's Official Page]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20111112085411/http://www.inceptiongallery.com/ Inception Gallery website]\n*[https://rulegallery.com/artist/sandy-skoglund/ Rule Gallery]\n*Skoglund, Sandy. ''[http://museums.fivecolleges.edu/detail.php?museum=sc&record=0&v=2&s=Babies+at+Paradise+Pond&type=all&t=objects&f=&d= Babies at Paradise Pond]''. 1996. Five Colleges and Historic Deerfield Museum Consortium, Smith College.\n\n==Further reading==\n*Faulconer Gallery, Daniel Strong, Milton Severe, Marvin Heiferman, and Douglas Dreishpoon. ''Raining Popcorn: Sandy Skoglund''. Grinnell, Iowa: Grinnell College, Faulconer Gallery, 2001.\n*{{cite book |last1=Rosenblum |first1=Naomi |title=A history of women photographers |date=2014 |publisher=Abbeville |location=New York |oclc=946544670 }}\n*Rosenblum, Robert, Linda Muehlig, Ann H. Sievers, Carol Squiers, and Sandy Skoglund. ''[http://www.worldcat.org/oclc/957640487 Sandy Skoglund: Reality Under Siege] : a Retrospective''. London: Harry N. Abrams, 1998.\n*{{cite book |last1=Skoglund |first1=Sandy |title=Sandy Skoglund : 28 d'abril al 31 de maig 1992 |date=1992 |publisher=Sala Catalunya de la Fundaci\u00f3 \"La Caixa\" |location=Barcelona |oclc=27437229 }}\n*{{cite book |last1=Skoglund |first1=Sandy |title=The artificial mirror |date=2009 |publisher=Contrasto due srl |location=Roma |oclc=693751458 }}\n*\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Skoglund, Sandy}}\n[[Category:1946 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American people of Swedish descent]]\n[[Category:American women photographers]]\n[[Category:Smith College alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Paris alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Iowa alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Hartford faculty]]\n[[Category:Rutgers University faculty]]\n[[Category:20th-century American photographers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women artists]]\n[[Category:Photographers from Iowa]]\n[[Category:21st-century American photographers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox artist\n| name          = Sandy Skoglund\n| image= Artist Sandy Skoglund, 2013 (cropped).jpg\n| caption=Skoglund in 2013\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1946|9|11|mf=y}}\n| birth_place   = [[Weymouth, Massachusetts]], U.S.\n| nationality   = American\n| field         = [[Photography]], [[Sculpture]], [[installation art|Installation]]\n| training      = [[Smith College]], [[Massachusetts]] / [[University of Iowa]], [[Iowa]]\n| movement      = [[Surrealism]]\n| works         = ''Radioactive Cats'' (1980)<br/>''Sock Situation'' (1986)<br/>''The Cocktail Party'' (1992)<br/>''Shimmering Madness'' (1998)<br/>''Raining Pop Corn'' (2001)\n}}\n\n'''Sandy Skoglund''' (born September 11, 1946) is an American photographer and installation artist.<ref>{{cite news\n|title=Art in Review\n|author=Charles Hagen\n|date=September 23, 1994\n|newspaper=[[dagbladet]]\n|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/09/23/arts/art-in-review-329347.html?pagewanted=1?pagewanted=1\n|accessdate=2010-07-22\n}}</ref>\n\nSkoglund creates [[surrealist]] images by building elaborate sets or [[Tableaux Vivant|tableaux]], furnishing them with carefully selected colored furniture and other objects, a process of which takes her months to complete. Finally, she photographs the set, mostly including live models.  The works are characterized by an overwhelming amount of one object and either bright, contrasting colors or a monochromatic color scheme.<ref>[http://www.artnet.com/artist/659254/sandy-skoglund.html]</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nSkoglund was born in [[Weymouth, Massachusetts]] on September 11, 1946. She spent her childhood all over the country including the states Maine, Connecticut, and California. She studied both [[art history]] and [[studio art]] at [[Smith College]] in [[Northampton, Massachusetts|Northampton]], Massachusetts, graduating in 1968. In 1967, she studied art history through her college's study abroad program at the [[University of Paris|Sorbonne]] and [[\u00c9cole du Louvre]] in [[Paris]], [[France]]. After graduating in 1969, she went to graduate school at the [[University of Iowa]], where she studied [[cinematography|filmmaking]], [[multimedia]] [[art]], and [[printmaking]]. In 1971, she earned her Master of Arts and in 1972 a Master of Fine Arts in [[painting]].<ref>{{cite web\n |title        = Sandy Skogland Biography\n |publisher    = Art Galleries Switzerland\n |url          = http://guybae.artgalleries.ch/index.html?page_id=18&change_lid=1\n |accessdate   = 2007-08-26\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20070929004123/http://guybae.artgalleries.ch/index.html?page_id=18&change_lid=1#\n |archive-date = 2007-09-29\n |url-status     = dead\n}}</ref>\n\nIn 1972, Skoglund began working as a conceptual artist in [[New York City]]. She taught herself photography to document her artistic endeavors, and experimenting with themes of repetition.  She also become interested in advertising and high technology--trying to marry the commercial look with a noncommercial purpose, combining the technical focus found in the commercial world and bringing that into the fine art studio.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Tarlow|first=Lois|date=|title=Sandy Skoglund|url=|journal=Art New England|volume=19|pages=25|via=Art & Architecture Source}}</ref> Skoglund created repetitive, process-oriented art  through the techniques of mark-making and photocopying. For example, her 1973 ''Crumpled and Copied'' artwork centered on her repeatedly crumpled and photocopied a piece of paper.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.oxfordartonline.com/groveart/view/10.1093/gao/9781884446054.001.0001/oao-9781884446054-e-7000097698|title=Skoglund, Sandy|website=Grove Art Online|year=2002|language=en|doi=10.1093/gao/9781884446054.article.t097698|access-date=2020-03-31|last1=Grant|first1=Catherine M.}}</ref> In 1978, she had produced a series of repetitious food item still life images. These photographs of food were presented in geometric and brightly colored environments so that the food becomes an integral part to the overall patterning, as in Cubed Carrots and Kernels of Corn,<ref name=\":0\" />with its checkerboard of carrots on a white-spotted red plate placed on a cloth in the same pattern.  Skoglund's works are quirky and idiosyncratic, and as former photography critic for [[The New York Times]] [[Andy Grundberg]] describes, they \"evoke adult fears in a playful, childlike context\".\n\nOne of her most-known works, entitled ''Radioactive Cats'', features green-painted clay cats running amok in a gray kitchen. An older man sits in a chair with his back facing the camera while his elderly wife looks into a refrigerator that is the same color as the walls. \"The artist sculpted the life-size cats herself using chicken wire and plaster, and painted them bright green. She acquired used furniture and constructed a painted gray set, then asked two elderly neighbors living in her apartment building in New York City to pose as models.\"<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Dalton|first=Robert|date=|title=Interpreting and Responding to Contemporary Photography through Creative Writing.|url=|journal=Canadian Review of Art Education: Research & Issues|volume=42|pages=12\u201326|via=Art & Architecture Source}}</ref> The end product is a very evocative photograph.  In an on-line  Getty Center for Education in the Arts forum,Terry Barrett and Sydney Walker (2013) identify two viable interpretations of Radioactive Cats. The first is about social indifference to the elderly and the second is nuclear war and its aftermath, suggested by the artist\u2019s title.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nHer 1990 work, \"Fox Games'' has a similar feel to ''Radioactive Cats\";it unleashes the imagination of the viewer is allowed to roam freely. A third and final often recognized piece by her features numerous fish hovering above people in bed late at night and is called [[Revenge of the Goldfish (photograph)|Revenge of the Goldfish]].  The piece was used as cover art for the [[Inspiral Carpets]] album of the same name.<ref>[http://www.artcyclopedia.com/artists/skoglund_sandy.html]</ref>\n\nSkoglund was an art professor at the [[University of Hartford]] between 1973 and 1976. She is currently teaching photography and art installation/multimedia at [[Rutgers University]] in [[New Jersey]].\n\nIn 2000, the Galerie Guy B\u00e4rtschi in Geneva, Switzerland held an exhibition of 30 works by Sandy Skoglund, which served as a modest retrospective. The photographs ranged from the plates on tablecloths of the late 1970s to the more spectacular works of the 1980s and 1990s. The critic who reviewed the exhibition, Richard Leydier, commented that Skoglund criticism is littered with interpretations of all kinds, whether feminist, sociological, psychoanalytical or whatever. But, Skoglund claims not to be aware of these reading, saying, \"What is the meaning of my work? For me, it's really in doing it.\"<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Leydier|first=Richard|date=|title=Sandy Skoglund: Galerie Guy B\u00e4rtschi.|url=|journal=Art-Press|volume=no. 257|pages=65\u201366|via=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, Skoglund completed a series titled \"True Fiction Two\". This project is similar to the \"True Fiction\" series that she began in 1986. This series was not completed due to the discontinuation of materials that Skoglund was using. Kodak canceled the production of the dye that Skoglund was using for her prints. Each image in \"True Fiction Two\" has been meticulously crafted to assimilate the visual and photographic possibilities now available in digital processes.\n\nHer works are held in numerous museum collections including the [[Museum of Contemporary Photography]],<ref>[http://www.mocp.org/collections/permanent/skoglund_sandy.php mocp.org]</ref> [[San Francisco Museum of Modern Art]]<ref>[http://www.sfmoma.org/artists/4301/artwork sfmoma.org] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100728025508/http://www.sfmoma.org/artists/4301/artwork |date=2010-07-28 }}</ref>, [[Montclair Art Museum]] and [[Dayton Art Institute]].<ref>http://www.daytonartinstitute.org/art/collection-highlights/american/shimmering-madness</ref>\n\nSkoglund holds a faculty position at the Department of Arts, Culture and Media of [[University of Rutgers\u2013Newark]] in [[Newark, New Jersey]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [http://www.sandyskoglund.com/ Sandy Skoglund's Official Page]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20111112085411/http://www.inceptiongallery.com/ Inception Gallery website]\n*[https://rulegallery.com/artist/sandy-skoglund/ Rule Gallery]\n*Skoglund, Sandy. ''[http://museums.fivecolleges.edu/detail.php?museum=sc&record=0&v=2&s=Babies+at+Paradise+Pond&type=all&t=objects&f=&d= Babies at Paradise Pond]''. 1996. Five Colleges and Historic Deerfield Museum Consortium, Smith College.\n\n==Further reading==\n*Faulconer Gallery, Daniel Strong, Milton Severe, Marvin Heiferman, and Douglas Dreishpoon. ''Raining Popcorn: Sandy Skoglund''. Grinnell, Iowa: Grinnell College, Faulconer Gallery, 2001.\n*{{cite book |last1=Rosenblum |first1=Naomi |title=A history of women photographers |date=2014 |publisher=Abbeville |location=New York |oclc=946544670 }}\n*Rosenblum, Robert, Linda Muehlig, Ann H. Sievers, Carol Squiers, and Sandy Skoglund. ''[http://www.worldcat.org/oclc/957640487 Sandy Skoglund: Reality Under Siege] : a Retrospective''. London: Harry N. Abrams, 1998.\n*{{cite book |last1=Skoglund |first1=Sandy 