ess, 2017, ''Peoples of the Eastern Habsburg Lands, 1526-1918'', p. 446</ref>   \n*28 November - The Romanian National Council, together with Polish and German representatives, convokes the [[General Congress of Bukovina]] which requests the union of Bukovina with Romania.<ref>Robert A. Kann, Zdenek David, University of Washington Press, 2017, ''Peoples of the Eastern Habsburg Lands, 1526-1918'', p. 446</ref><ref>Keith Hitchins, Clarendon Press, 1994, ''Rumania 1866-1947'', p. 279</ref>\n*19 December - The Romanian Government issues a decree formalizing Bukovina's annexation.<ref>Robert A. Kann, Zdenek David, University of Washington Press, 2017, ''Peoples of the Eastern Habsburg Lands, 1526-1918'', p. 446</ref>\n\n===1919===\n*10 September - The [[Treaty of Saint-Germain-en-Laye (1919)|Treaty of Saint-Germain-en-Laye]] is signed, recognizing Romanian sovereignity over Bukovina (frontiers of Romania was to be later fixed).<ref name=\"Martin2007\">{{cite book|author=Lawrence Martin|title=The Treaties of Peace, 1919-1923|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jtyOqiwiDLYC&pg=PA1091|year=2007|publisher=The Lawbook Exchange, Ltd.|isbn=978-1-58477-708-3|pages=1091\u2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Cornis-Pope\">Marcel Cornis-Pope, John Neubauer, John Benjamins Publishing, 2006, ''History of the Literary Cultures of East-Central Europe: Junctures and disjunctures in the 19th and 20th centuries, Volume 2'', p. 58</ref><ref>Richard C. Hall, ABC-CLIO, 2014, ''War in the Balkans: An Encyclopedic History from the Fall of the Ottoman Empire to the Breakup of Yugoslavia'', p. 50</ref>\n\n===1920===\n*10 August - The S\u00e8vres frontier's Treaty established the Romanian-Polish boundary (mainly, based on the July 1919 Lw\u00f3w Convention).<ref name=\"Cornis-Pope\"/><ref name=\"Ciorteanu\">{{cite journal |last=Ciorteanu |first=Cezar |date=July 2014 |title=Politico-Territorial Projects concerning Bukovina and the Romanian-Polish Border in the Context of Diplomatic Negotiations during and after World War I (1914-1920) |url=http://atlas.usv.ro/www/codru_net/page20_1r.html |journal=Codrul Cosminului |volume=XX |issue=1 |pages=113-148 |issn=2067-5860 |access-date=25 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nImage:Bukowina Donaumonarchie.png|Bukovina within Austria-Hungary\nImage:Flag of Bukowina.svg|Flag of Bukovina\nImage:West-Ukraine 1918.jpg|Division of Bukovina (orange) as claimed by the West Ukrainian People's Republic (black interrupted line)\nImage:Bucov.png|Ethnic map of Bukovina (purple = Romanians, green = Ukrainians)\nImage:Iancu Ritter von Flondor um 1900.jpg|Iancu Flondor\n</gallery>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Romanian occupation of Pokuttya]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:1918 in Romania]]\n[[Category:National unifications|Romania]]\n[[Category:Greater Romania]]\n", "name_user": "JHunterJ", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up,typo(s) fixed: sovereignity \u2192 sovereignty", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Union_of_Bukovina_with_the_Kingdom_of_Romania"}
{"title_page": "Mount Abraham (Vermont)", "text_new": "{{for|other uses of this name|Mount Abraham (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox mountain\n| name = Mount Abraham\n| photo = Mt Abe.jpg\n| photo_caption = View of Mount Abraham from the west\n| map = Vermont\n| map_alt = Mount Abraham in the State of Vermont in the United States\n| map_caption = Vermont, U.S.A.\n| map_relief = yes\n| map_size = 200\n| elevation_ft = 4006\n| elevation_ref = <ref name=\"GMC Long Trail map\" />\n| prominence_ft = 286\n| prominence_ref = <ref>{{cite peakbagger |pid=7023 |name=Mount Abraham, Vermont |accessdate=2008-12-11}}</ref>\n| listing = [[Four-thousand footers|New England 4,000 footers]]\n| country = [[United States]]\n| state = [[Vermont]]\n| district = [[Addison County, Vermont|Addison]]\n| district_type = County\n| city = [[Lincoln, Vermont|Lincoln]]\n| city_type = Town\n| range = [[Presidential Range (Green Mountains)|Presidential Range]], [[Green Mountains]]\n| range_coordinates = \n| label_position = right\n| coordinates = {{coord|44|07|14|N|072|56|10|W |type:mountain_region:US-VT_scale:100000_source:ngs|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| coordinates_ref = <ref name=\"GNIS\" />\n| topo = [[United States Geological Survey|USGS]] Lincoln Mountain Quad<ref name=\"USGS 1921\" />\n| type = \n| age = \n| first_ascent = \n| easiest_route = \n}}\n\n'''Mount Abraham''' (known as '''Mount Abe''' to locals) is a mountain in the [[Green Mountains]] in the [[U.S. state]] of [[Vermont]]. Located in the [[Green Mountain National Forest]], its summit is in the town of [[Lincoln, Vermont|Lincoln]] in [[Addison County, Vermont|Addison County]], but its eastern slopes extend into the town of [[Warren, Vermont|Warren]] in [[Washington County, Vermont|Washington County]]. The mountain is named after [[Abraham Lincoln]], former president of the United States.<ref name=\"Bushnell 2019\" /> It is one of five peaks in Vermont's [[Presidential Range (Green Mountains)|Presidential Range]].\n\nAt {{convert|4006|feet|1}}, Mount Abraham is the highest point in Addison County, the fifth highest peak in Vermont, and one of the [[List of New England Hundred Highest|hundred highest peaks in New England]]. Its summit supports a small amount of [[alpine tundra]] vegetation.\n\n==History==\n\nChartered in 1780, the town of Lincoln is named after [[American Revolutionary War]] hero [[Benjamin Lincoln]],<ref name=\"lincolnvermont.org\" /> not Abraham Lincoln as might be expected. Nearby [[Lincoln Peak (Vermont)|Lincoln Peak]] is also named after Benjamin Lincoln.<ref name=\"Bushnell 2019\" /> In Addison County, all place names containing the word \u201cLincoln\u201d pre-date the birth of Abraham Lincoln.\n \nPotatoes were once an important agricultural crop in Lincoln, which explains why the mountain was previously known as Potato Hill.<ref name=\"ngs\" /> Use of the current name dates back to at least 1921 when the [[USGS]] began annotating various maps with the name Mount Abraham.<ref name=\"USGS 1921\" />\n\nOn June&nbsp;28, 1973, a pilot flying from Twin Mountain, New Hampshire to [[Newburgh, New York]] was maneuvering to avoid clouds when he hit trees on the north ridge of Mount Abraham. He and two passengers survived the plane crash.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ntsb.gov/_layouts/ntsb.aviation/brief.aspx?ev_id=86260&key=0|title=NTSB Identification: NYC73FNC76|last=National Transportation Safety Board|website=www.ntsb.gov|access-date=2019-08-24}}</ref> However, parts of the plane (a [[Cessna 182 Skylane|Cessna 182N]], registration number N92431) are still on the mountain today.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://4000footers.com/abraham.shtml|title=Hike mount abraham vermont 4000 footers VT Mt Abraham Green mountains|website=4000footers.com|access-date=2016-09-20}}</ref><ref name=\"Obscure Vermont\" />\n\n==Drainage basin==\n\nMount Abraham stands within the [[drainage basin|watershed]] of [[Lake Champlain]], which drains into the [[Richelieu River]] in [[Qu\u00e9bec]], the [[Saint Lawrence River]], and then eventually into the [[Gulf of Saint Lawrence]]. The southeast slopes of Mount Abraham drain into Lincoln Brook, then into the [[Mad River (Vermont)|Mad River]], the [[Winooski River]], and into Lake Champlain. The east slopes drain into Bradley Brook, a tributary of the Mad River. The southwest face of Mount Abraham drains into the [[headwaters]] of the [[New Haven River]], [[Otter Creek (Vermont)|Otter Creek]], and into Lake Champlain. The northwest face of Mount Abraham drains into Beaver Meadow Brook, a tributary of the New Haven River.\n\n==Hiking==\n\nThe [[Long Trail]] traverses the summit of Mount Abraham. A popular day hike begins and ends where the Long Trail crosses Lincoln Gap Road in the town of Lincoln. From Lincoln Gap, the summit is {{convert|2.6|mile|1}} north on the Long Trail. Alternatively, the Battell Trail, whose trailhead is also in Lincoln, terminates at the Battell Shelter after {{convert|2.0|mile|1}}. From the shelter, the summit is {{convert|0.9|mile|1}} north on the Long Trail.<ref name=\"GMC Long Trail map\" />\n\nMount Abraham offers one of the best panoramas on the entire Long Trail.<ref name=\"GMC Day Hiker\" /> Beyond the [[Champlain Valley]] {{convert|10|mile|0}} to the west, stands [[Mount Marcy]] and the [[Adirondack Mountains]]. In the opposite direction, one can see the [[White Mountains (New Hampshire)|White Mountains]] of [[New Hampshire]] {{convert|80|mile|0}} to the east. To the south, [[Killington Peak]] may be seen {{convert|40|mile|0}} away.\n\n{{Gallery\n| title        = \n| align        =\n| footer       =\n| style        =\n| state        =\n| height       =\n| width        =\n| captionstyle =\n| File:Mt Ellen Vermont seen from Mt Abraham.jpg\n | alt1=A view of Mount Ellen seen from Mount Abraham\n | Mount Ellen seen from Mount Abraham\n}}\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[List of mountains in Vermont]]\n* [[List of New England Hundred Highest]]\n\n== References ==\n\n{{Reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=\